   {:e #blake3 "99d572e33b848f12421296004495ea62d2f8f6ec393f46d2de1a3239f1477efd" :a :task/description :v "BACKGROUND: Every braid command rebuilds the 46K-datom store from 4400+ .edn files when the cache is stale. FD-012 (every command writes a tx) means the cache is stale after EVERY command. This is the single largest friction in the workflow (15-30s per status). MaterializedViews fixed F(S) computation to O(1), but the load-from-disk is still O(n). The daemon (CE-7) is the ultimate fix, but incremental caching delivers 90% of the benefit immediately.. APPROACH: (1) Alongside store.bin cache, persist last_tx_hashes: HashSet<String> (the set of tx file hashes at cache write time). (2) On load_store(): compute current_hashes, compare to last_tx_hashes. (3) If identical: full cache hit (existing fast path). (4) If delta = current - last is non-empty: load cached store, then for each hash in delta: read TxFile, build Transaction<Committed>, call store.transact(tx). (5) Rewrite cache with updated store + new last_tx_hashes. (6) Append-only store guarantees: deletions never happen (C1), so current - last is always additions. (7) Edge case: if last_tx_hashes contains hashes not in current (impossible under C1, but defensive): fall back to full rebuild.. ACCEPTANCE: (A) incremental_load(cached_store, 1_new_tx) completes in < 100ms. (B) incremental_load produces identical datom_set to full_load (CRDT property: S union T1 == from_datoms(all)). (C) 0 new txns = instant cache hit (existing behavior). (D) 1-5 new txns (common case after FD-012) = < 200ms. (E) Proptest: for random tx sequences, incremental == full (datom set equality).. FILE: crates/braid/src/layout.rs" :op :assert}
